commitResults.messageTitle: Update User Guide to explain usage of Add function
Add internship application stage attribute to internship class
commitResults.messageBody:
We want to keep track of the stage of application we are at so we know what to expect
next in the application.

Let's add a new field to `AddCommand` and `EditCommand` to include `stage` attribute.

This follows the conventional way of adding and editing  an internship.
As internship application is a process, allowing edits to the stage is
justifiable.

Let's also edit the JUnit tests for these respective classes
to reflect the changes in the main code. Respective JSON files
used in testcases are updated as well.

However, not advised to follow this chunky commit method.

Let's allow the input of dates so that the user can keep track
of their internship application stage dates.

Let's also allow the date format to be how we usually write them
(i.e. DD-MM-YYYY) to allow users to input at a faster speed.

commitResults.messageTitle: Update `add` command to allow optional dates
commitResults.messageBody:
This allows users to keep track of when the next important
date is, and subsequently be well-prepared before the date.

It is made optional to allow flexibility of recording dates.

Minor changes to essential logic code to allow addition
of optional date to each internship application.

Let's also update the logic for `edit` command to
allow compilation of the code.

Let's update `Stage` to include checks for those with curated tips.
In this manner, frontend can call this method to determine if the input stage

commitResults.messageTitle: Update message displayed for added internships
commitResults.messageBody:
Let's notify the user if they added a stage that was not prepared
beforehand by us. If it is something related, they can easily edit the
stage to suit our pre-defined list and get some tips.

This encourages flexibility for the user, instead of outwright rejection.

Testcases are not updated as of this commit.

Let's add this class to contain the constants and utility methods
for `Stage` class. It helps map each `Stage` to a list of curated tips.

Let's fix some code quality issues too to ensure mutual
understanding between developers.

Let's remove `Stage` level methods declared in `Model`, `ModelManager
,`WorkBook` and `VersionedWorkBook` to comply to OOP standards.

Let's also make the elements in `StageUtil` to be `private` to prevent
manipulation from the outside world. Getters are implemented to
retrieve the elements instead.

Improve documentation of methods as well to allow more
effective comunication between developers.

commitResults.messageTitle: Rename classes to match tP product name, "WorkBook"
commitResults.messageBody:
Class names from AB3 are unintuitive for development work as they do not
fit with WorkBook (e.g AddressBookStorage.java, AddressBookParser.java
etc)

Let's perform a project-wide refactoring of all class names to use
WorkBook and appropriate phrasing to remove any semblance to AB3.
This includes .json files as well.

Note: remnants of AB3 phrasing are still present, e.g .md and .puml
files.

More refactoring commits to be followed.

commitResults.messageTitle: Rename primary domain from Person to Internship.
commitResults.messageBody:
Class, attribute and method names are unintuitive as they are carried
over from AB3 to WorkBook (e.g PersonBuilder.java, UniquePersonList.java
etc).

Let's perform an overhaul of all these inappropriate names in the
project so that all development work will be standardised from here on
out (e.g PersonBuilder.java -> InternshipBuilder.java)

Let's also change the attribute of Person.name to Internship.company,
making the appropriate changes in all test/util/other files (e.g
NameContainsKeywordsPredicate.java ->
CompanyContainsKeywordsPredicate.java)

This completes the bulk of the refactoring from AB3 to WorkBook.
CRUD functionality is now fully working, and all test cases are passing at
this stage, although mock data still does not match WorkBook's context.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add Role field to an Internship
commitResults.messageBody:
An Internship should not only have a Company name, but also a Role (e.g
Backend Engineer).

Let's add an attribute to the Internship Model, and make the necessary
changes to all test files as well.

One can think of Company name and Role as a "primary key" or unique
identifier for an Internship in WorkBook. As such, we should allow for
entries that have the same Company as long as they have different Roles.

Take a look at Internship#isSameInternship for this functionality (this
method is used throughout the codebase e.g during Edit, loading from
.json, etc)

commitResults.messageTitle: Remove trailing whitespace as enforced by run-checks.sh

commitResults.messageBody:
Note that certain rules enforced by checkstyle.xml are inappropriate such as
the enforcing of `SeparatorWrap` on lambda functions (see
UniqueInternshipListTest.java:168 for e.g).

As such, we should exercise some discretion and use the provided
`SuppressionCommentFilter` in `checkstyle.xml`
to disable checkstyle within a specific code chunk and with
respect to a specific `rule` (again see UniqueInternshipListTest.java)

In order to disable certain rules that are higher up the inheritance
chain in `checkstyle.xml` (rules defined outside the `TreeWalker` module), we can add `SuppressionWithPlainTextCommentFilter` to the `Checker` module. (See checkstyle.xml:13)

This allows us to suppress rules like `LineLength` using the same syntax
(see Company.java and Role.java for e.g)

Finally, note that these suppressions should not be abused, but only
used if the enforced rule clearly degrades code quality/readability.

Change behaviour of Edit to not reset filtering
commitResults.messageBody:
If one uses Find followed by Edit, the filtering resets (as if List had
been used).

It does not seem very user friendly and is also somewhat
disruptive/jarring based on my own testing.

Let's remove this behaviour, so that Edit does not reset any Predicates
imposed on the internal internship list.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add util methods to DateTime to support comparison
commitResults.messageBody:
Let's add some util methods to DateTime and use them in our custom InternshipComparator.

Note the checks for `DateTime.EMPTY_DATETIME` in the comparator.

Comparison will follow the ordering as specified in the Developer Guide.

commitResults.messageTitle: Ensure internship list is always sorted
commitResults.messageBody:
Note the minor fix in `InternshipComparator.java`.
Originally the comparison would be wrong if `o1` was a upcoming date and
`o2` was a date that had passed already.

Let's use better dates (upcoming, past, blank) so that new users can actually get an idea of the
enforced sorting in WorkBook.

Failing test cases exposed another weakness in the InternshipComparator.
A desirable characteristic of our comparator (especially for testing) is unambiguity, so let's further specify how we want two empty datetimes to be sorted - by lexicographical order of Company name.

Also, we have to fix the `equals` method on UniqueInternshipList.java as
equality should only be checked w.r.t the sorted list and not the
internal list as that is the external facing interface anyway. This
fixes all the remaining test cases that were failing.

Let's make a distinction between misc. tags and Language tags which a
user can use to indicate what languages they should be proficient in for
a certain application.

Considered making a new class to extend from `Tag.java` but decided it
was not worth the effort, so `languageTags` are basically a separate
`Set` of Tags. (and will be rendered differently later)

commitResults.messageTitle: Add specific styling for Language Tags
commitResults.messageBody:
We define a custom component class `LanguageTagLabel.java` so that we
can still insert all our tags into the same `FlowPane` but apply
different styling based on `.setStyleClass()`.

commitResults.messageTitle: Put first card into focus upon app start
commitResults.messageBody:
This makes the ux more intuitive as the right panel will not just be
blank initially.

We should not show tips when no card is selected. This occurs for
example when `clear` is executed. If not, the last selected tip will
remain.

We should also set the correct panel upon startup instead of having to
wait for the user to resize the window for the event listener to pick up
on the changes.
